data.name: label31.Text
data.value: In CubeX, once the solution is generated, you can easily scroll through and perform the algorithm on your Cube. Even if you are'nt much familiar with the notations, with the animated view of Cube turns you'll be able to solve your Cube without any fuss. For scrolling through the algorithm, you may also make use the arrow keys on the keyboard, apart from the buttons for ease.

data.name: label19.Text
data.value: There are 6 faces: right (R), left (L), up (U), down (D), front (F), and back (B). Exactly which colors are on each face will depend on how you hold the Cube, but it's usually most convenient to talk about these relative moves instead of the face colors. Each face can be rotated in two different directions. Clockwise or counter-clockwise means that direction as seen when you're looking straight at that face. Another way to figure it out is to use a right hand rule. Point your right thumb out away from the face in question, and curl your fingers. The direction of their curl is always counter-clockwise.

data.name: label5.Text
data.value: Rubik's Cube enthusiasts use a notation developed by David Singmaster to denote a sequence of moves, referred to as "Singmaster notation". Its relative nature allows algorithms to be written in such a way that they can be applied regardless of which side is designated the top or how the colours are organised on a particular Cube.

data.name: Input_Label.Text
data.value: Fill the empty cubelets by referring the colors on your scrambled Rubik's Cube and fill every six faces accordingly. Please note that it is important to consider the alignment of the side faces while entering the state. So make sure that the side faces (shown in little rectangular boxes on the sides of each faces) match before starting the input on each face. (A face is decided by looking at the color of cubelet at the center of that face).
